head(df)
total_visitors_monuments <- df %>%
  group_by(Monuments) %>%
  summarise(Total_Visitors = sum(`2020-21`, `2021-22`, `2022-23`)) %>%
  arrange(desc(Total_Visitors))

# Get the top 15 monuments
top_15_monuments <- head(total_visitors_monuments, 15)
least_15_monuments <- tail(total_visitors_monuments, 15)
# Create a bar plot for the top 10 monuments
ggplot(top_15_monuments, aes(x = reorder(Monuments, Total_Visitors), y = Total_Visitors, fill = Monuments)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 15 Monuments by Total Visitors",
       x = "Monuments",
       y = "Total Visitors") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

ggplot(least_15_monuments, aes(x = reorder(Monuments, Total_Visitors), y = Total_Visitors, fill = Monuments)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "least 15 Monuments by Total Visitors",
       x = "Monuments",
       y = "Total Visitors") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

total_visitors_cities <- df %>%
  group_by(city) %>%

total_monuments_per_city <- df %>%

  summarise(Total_Monuments = n_distinct(Monuments))

total_visitors_by_year_type <- df %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarise(
    Total_Visitors_2020_21 = sum(`2020-21`, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Visitors_2021_22 = sum(`2021-22`, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Visitors_2022_23 = sum(`2022-23`, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

long_total_visitors <- total_visitors_by_year_type %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = Total_Visitors_2020_21:Total_Visitors_2022_23, 
               names_to = "Year", 
               values_to = "Total_Visitors")

long_total_visitors$Year <- gsub("Total_Visitors_", "", long_total_visitors$Year)


ggplot(long_total_visitors, aes(x = Year, y = Total_Visitors, color = type, group = type)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +      # Line plot for visitors
  geom_point(size = 3) +     # Points on the line
  labs(title = "Overlay of Domestic and Foreign Visitors Over the Years (2020-21 to 2022-23)",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Total Visitors") +
  theme_linedraw()

total_visitors_by_city_type <- df %>%
  group_by(city, type) %>%
  summarise(
    Total_Visitors_2020_21 = sum(`2020-21`, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Visitors_2021_22 = sum(`2021-22`, na.rm = TRUE),
    Total_Visitors_2022_23 = sum(`2022-23`, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  mutate(Total_Visitors = Total_Visitors_2020_21 + Total_Visitors_2021_22 + Total_Visitors_2022_23)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'city'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(total_visitors_by_city_type, aes(x = city, y = Total_Visitors, fill = type)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack") +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Domestic and Foreign Visitors Across Cities",
       x = "City",
       y = "Total Visitors") +
  theme_light() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

city_totals <-df %>%
  mutate(Total_Visitors = `2020-21` + `2021-22` + `2022-23`) %>%
  group_by(city) %>%
  summarise(Total_Visitors = sum(Total_Visitors)) %>%
  arrange(desc(Total_Visitors))


top_3_cities <- head(city_totals, 3)


top_cities_data <- df %>%
  filter(city %in% top_3_cities$city) %>%
  mutate(Total_Visitors = `2020-21` + `2021-22` + `2022-23`)

# Step 4:  density plot
ggplot(top_cities_data, aes(x = Total_Visitors, fill = city)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5, adjust = 1.5) +  # Adjust bandwidth for smoother curves
  facet_wrap(~type) +  # Facet by visitor type, and use free scales for each facet
  labs(title = "Density Plot of Total Visitor Numbers by City and Type",
       x = "Total Number of Visitors",
       y = "Density") +
  scale_x_log10()

data_long <- df %>%
  select(city, Monuments, type, `2020-21`, `2021-22`, `2022-23`) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("20"), names_to = "Year", values_to = "Visitors")
top_monuments <- data_long %>%
  group_by(Monuments) %>%
  summarise(Total_Visitors = sum(Visitors)) %>%
  top_n(5, Total_Visitors) %>%
  pull(Monuments)

# Filter the original data for the top monuments
filtered_data <- data_long %>%
  filter(Monuments %in% top_monuments)

# Create the animated bar plot for the top 5 monuments
animated_bar_plot <- ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = reorder(Monuments, -Visitors), y = Visitors, fill = type)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = 'Top 5 Visitor Trends for Monuments',
       x = 'Monuments',
       y = 'Number of Visitors') +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  transition_time(as.numeric(factor(Year))) +
  ease_aes('linear')

animated_plot <- animate(animated_bar_plot, nframes = 100, fps = 10)
anim_save("animated_bar_plot.gif", animation = animated_plot)
print(animated_plot)
